value.value: The transcription of lncRNAs, non-coding RNAs over 200 nucleotides in length, from a DNA template.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the synthesis of a lncRNA.
Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the synthesis of a lncRNA.
The transcription of a small interfering RNA from an RNA template.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the breakdown of small interfering RNA transcripts (siRNAs).

label.value: positive regulation of regulation of ascospore wall (1->3)-beta-D-glucan biosynthetic process

value.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of ascospore wall (1->3)-beta-D-glucan biosynthetic process.
Catalysis of the reaction: phlorizin + H2O = beta-D-glucose + phloretin.

A histone octamer slider activity that spaces nucleosomes along chromosomal DNA. This activity is involved in assembling chromatin in uniform nucleosome arrays to regulate transcription by RNA polymerases I, II, and III, as well as DNA replication, recombination and repair.

definition.value: In Drosphila, this is mediated by ISWI, in human, by SMARCA5 and in S. cerevisiae by ISW1 and and ISW2.

value.value: A chromatin remodeler activity that slides core histone octamers along chromosomal DNA.

definition.value: This activity is mediated by at least three subfamilies of the SNF2 remodellers, namely the bromodomain domain, the chromodomain containing and the imitation switch subfamilies.

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: UDP-glucose + [(1->3)-beta-D-glucosyl](n) = UDP + a branched [(1->3)-beta-D-glucosyl](n+1).
Catalysis of the reaction: UDP-glucose + [(1->3)-beta-D-glucosyl](n) = UDP + a linear [(1->3)-beta-D-glucosyl](n+1).

label.value: reorganization of cellular membranes to establish viral sites of replication

value.value: A process in intracellular membranes are reorganized by viral proteins that perturb membrane integrity and can cause an extensive rearrangement of cellular membranes, forming membranous webs, which are thought to be the site of replication or certain viruses, for example the HPV virus.

label.value: reorganization of host cellular membranes to establish sites of replication

value.value: A process in which a virus triggers host intracellular membranes to be reorganized, forming membranous webs, which are thought to be the site of replication or certain viruses, for example the HPV virus.
The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of the proteasome.
An thiol-dependent isopeptidase activity that cleaves NEDD8 from a target protein to which it is conjugated.
An metal-dependent isopeptidase activity that cleaves NEDD8 from a target protein to which it is conjugated.

Catalysis of the reaction: S-adenosyl-L-methionine + histone H3 L-lysine (position 56) = S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + histone H3 N6-methyl-L-lysine (position 56). This reaction is the addition of a methyl group to the lysine residue at position 56 of the histone H3 protein.
Catalysis of the removal of a methyl group from a tri or a dimethyl-lysine residue at position 56 of the histone H3 protein.
Catalysis of the reactions: nucleoside 3',5'-cyclic AMP + H2O = AMP + H+; this activity is activated by binding to calcium-bound calmodulin.
Catalysis of the reaction: a quinone + D-glucose = a quinol + D-glucono-1,5-lactone.

label.value: programmed DNA elimination by elimination of internal DNA segments

value.value: A programmed DNA elimination mechanism in which specific sequences, namely, internal eliminated sequences (IES) and breakage eliminated sequences (BES) are removed from the genome. This process is known to occur in ciliates.

label.value: small RNA binding translational repressor activity

value.value: A translational repressor activity that binds to a single-stranded small regulatory RNA (either a miRNA or a siRNA) to guide it to its target mRNA.

definition.value: This term is intended for activities such as that mediated by argonaute in the RISC complex, that bring a miRNA or an siRNA to their target mRNA.

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: histone H3 N6-acetyl-L-lysine (position 56) + H2O = histone H3 L-lysine (position 56) + acetate. This reaction requires the presence of NAD, and represents the removal of an acetyl group from lysine at position 56 of the histone H3 protein.

A post-transcriptional gene silencing pathway in which small interfering RNAs (siRNAs) elicit silencing of specific target genes. siRNAs are 21-23 nucleotide RNA duplexes that are fully complementary to their target mRNA. siRNAs can be exported and act in other cells, including in germline cells. Once incorporated into a RNA-induced silencing complex (RISC), siRNAs can downregulate gene expression by either of two posttranscriptional mechanisms: endonucleolytic cleavage of the mRNA or mRNA translational repression. siRNAs are present in lower animals and plants, but not found in mammals; whereas miRNAs are present in all the animals and in plants.
An adaptor that brings together an enzyme and its substrate. Adaptors recruit the substrate to its enzyme, thus contributing to substrate selection and specificity.
An enzyme-substrate adaptor that bings together a protein ADP-ribosyl transferase and its substrate.
Catalysis of the reaction: L-lysyl-[protein] + tetradecanoyl-[ACP] = H+ + holo-[ACP] + N(6)-tetradecanoyl-L-lysyl-[protein].
Catalysis of the reaction: L-lysyl-[protein] + tetradecanoyl-CoA = CoA + H+ + N(6)-tetradecanoyl-L-lysyl-[protein].
Catalysis of the reaction: hexadecanoyl-[ACP] + L-lysyl-[protein] = H+ + holo-[ACP] + N(6)-hexadecanoyl-L-lysyl-[protein].
Catalysis of the reaction: L-lysyl-[protein] + hexadecanoyl-CoA = CoA + H+ + N(6)-hexadecanoyl-L-lysyl-[protein].
Catalysis of the reaction: N6-tetradecanoyl-L-lysyl-[protein] + NAD+ + H2O = tetradecanoyl-ADP-D-ribose + L-lysyl-[protein] + nicotinamide.
Catalysis of the reaction: N6-octadecanoyl-L-lysyl-[protein] + NAD+ + H2O = octadecanoyl-ADP-D-ribose + L-lysyl-[protein] + nicotinamide.
Binding to an actin filament and promoting the dissociation of an actin filament branch.

A molecular function that involves direct binding to one of the subunits of a protein-containing complex and promoting the dissociation of one or many subunits. This often happens by changing the conformation of the protein being bound, which decreases its affinity for the rest of the complex.
A molecular function that involves direct binding to one of the subunits of a protein-containing complex, thus preventing an interaction with a factor that would promote dissociation of the complex.
A protein-containing complex stabilizing activity that prevents dissociation of microtubules.
The appearance of XCL1 due to biosynthesis or secretion following a cellular stimulus, resulting in an increase in its intracellular or extracellular levels.

definition.value: Note that this term is in the subset of terms that should not be used for direct gene product annotation. Instead, select one of the 'regulation' children terms.

value.value: The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of ilicicolin H, a 4-hydroxy-2-pyridone alkaloid that has potent and broad antifungal activities by inhibiting the mitochondrial respiration chain.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of novofumigatonin, a heavily oxygenated meroterpenoid containing a unique orthoester moiety.
The chemical reactions and pathways resulting in the formation of (M)-viriditoxin, a fungal secondary metabolite with antibacterial activity.
Binding to and responding, e.g. by conformational change, to changes in the cellular level of a metal ion.
Binding to and responding, e.g. by conformational change, to changes in the cellular level of an amino acid.
Binding to and responding, e.g. by conformational change, to changes in the cellular level of glutamine.

Catalysis of the active transport of a phosphate ion across a membrane by a mechanism involving conformational change, where energy for active transport is derived from membrane potential if the solute is charged.

Catalysis of the active transport of a L-glutamate across a membrane by a mechanism involving conformational change, where energy for active transport is derived from membrane potential if the solute is charged.
Catalysis of the reaction: a phosphorylated histone + H2O = a protein + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: histone H2AX serine phosphate (position 140) + H2O = histone H2AX serine (position 140) + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: histone H2AX tyrosine phosphate (position 142) + H2O = histone H2AX tyrosine (position 142) + phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: H2O + histone 3 L-arginyl = histone 3 L-citrullyl + NH4+, resulting in histone citrullination.

definition.value: The substrate for histone deiminase may be methyl-arginine, rather than arginine (see PMID:35197210 and PMID:16567635).

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: H2O + histone H3 L-arginyl (position 2)= histone H3 L-citrullyl (position 2) + NH4+, resulting in histone H3 citrullination at position 2.

definition.value: The substrate for histone deiminase may be methyl-arginine, rather than arginine (see PMID:35197210 and PMID:16567635).
